Yes—there are signs of a swing back toward character, locality, and lived texture.

You can see it in:

* people restoring older homes instead of demolishing them,
* renewed interest in craftsman, mid-century, and vernacular styles,
* handmade materials gaining prestige,
* visible wood/brick/plaster returning,
* “cozy” aesthetics replacing sterile luxury,
* gardens and porches becoming desirable again,
* mixed-use walkable neighborhoods gaining appeal,
* and backlash against algorithmic sameness in general.

Part of it is economic fatigue with hyper-optimization.
Part is digital saturation.

When so much of life becomes:

* standardized,
* screen-mediated,
* and globally interchangeable,

people start craving:

* texture,
* friction,
* permanence,
* locality,
* and evidence of human touch.

It’s similar to:

* vinyl returning after streaming,
* film cameras after infinite digital photos,
* farmers markets after industrial food,
* physical books after endless feeds.

Not because the old systems were objectively superior in every way, but because optimization often removes the “signal of care.”

And once enough optimization accumulates, care itself becomes a luxury marker.

The pendulum rarely stops at one extreme. Systems tend to oscillate:

* abundance → commodification,
* commodification → flattening,
* flattening → hunger for authenticity,
* authenticity → scarcity premium,
* then eventually re-commercialization again.

That cycle shows up in architecture, culture, fashion, food, and even online identity.